{"id":"nlin/0104037","submitter":"Schief","authors":"W.K. Schief","title":"On the unification of classical and novel integrable surfaces: II.\n  Difference geometry","comments":"21 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.SI","license":null,"abstract":"  A novel class of discrete integrable surfaces is recorded. This class of\ndiscrete O surfaces is shown to include discrete analogues of classical\nsurfaces such as isothermic, `linear' Weingarten, Guichard and Petot surfaces.\nMoreover, natural discrete analogues of the Gaussian and mean curvatures for\nsurfaces parametrized in terms of curvature coordinates are used to define\nsurfaces of constant discrete Gaussian and mean curvatures and discrete minimal\nsurfaces. Remarkably, these turn out to be proto-typical examples of discrete O\nsurfaces. It is demonstrated that the construction of a Backlund transformation\nfor discrete O surfaces leads in a natural manner to an associated\nparameter-dependent linear representation. Canonical discretizations of the\nclassical pseudosphere and breather pseudospherical surfaces are generated.\nConnections with pioneering work by Bobenko and Pinkall are established.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Apr 2001 06:31:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"nucl-th/0104051","submitter":"Kristina D. Sviratcheva","authors":"K. D. Sviratcheva, A. I. Georgieva, V. G. Gueorguiev, J. P. Draayer\n  and M. I. Ivanov","title":"Deformations of the fermion realization of the sp(4) algebra and its\n  subalgebras","comments":"28 pages, LaTeX 12pt article style","journal-ref":"J.Phys.A34:8365-8382,2001","doi":"10.1088/0305-4470/34/40/312","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th math-ph math.GR math.MP math.QA math.RT","license":null,"abstract":"  With a view towards future applications in nuclear physics, the fermion\nrealization of the compact symplectic sp(4) algebra and its q-deformed versions\nare investigated. Three important reduction chains of the sp(4) algebra are\nexplored in both the classical and deformed cases. The deformed realizations\nare based on distinct deformations of the fermion creation and annihilation\noperators. For the primary reduction, the su(2) sub-structure can be\ninterpreted as either the spin, isospin or angular momentum algebra, whereas\nfor the other two reductions su(2) can be associated with pairing between\nfermions of the same type or pairing between two distinct fermion types. Each\nreduction provides for a complete classification of the basis states. The\ndeformed induced u(2) representations are reducible in the action spaces of\nsp(4) and are decomposed into irreducible representations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 16 Apr 2001 19:20:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 5 May 2001 00:12:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
